	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320010_01.jpg"/>
			<p>Committee to Collect Material</p>
			<p>about the Destruction of <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term> Jewry <date when="1939">1939</date></p>

			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_perkal_shloyme">Shloyme Perkal</persName>, 24 years</p>
			<p>Currently in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/593116/vilnius.html">Vilnius</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/593116/vilnius.html">Sadowa street 7</placeName></p>
			<p><date when="1939-11-12">12th November, 1939</date></p>

			<p>Testimony 10</p>

			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term> found me in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/764862/miedzyrzec-podlaski.html">Międzyrzec Podlaski</placeName>.</p>

			<p>Before <date when="1939-09-09">9th September</date> the town had not been touched by aerial <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombings</term>.</p>
			<p>The attitude of the local police toward the Jews changed considerably for the better.</p>

			<p>On the <date when="1939-09-09">9th [of September]</date> there were two <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombings</term>: a couple of times in the morning
				(but they missed the target), and about 4 p.m. in the vicinity (they set fire to villages on three sides of the town). It was said
				that a peasant was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">killed</term> during the first
				attack, and that there were 7-8 civilian <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-132" type="subject"
					>victims</term> (<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">killed</term> or wounded)
				during the second, among them about three Jews.</p>

			<p>By then <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/764862/miedzyrzec-podlaski.html">Międzyrzec</placeName> had already been flooded with
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304" type="subject">refugees</term>.</p>
			<p>On the <date when="1939-09-09">9th</date>, in spite of Shabbat, bakeries were working, and the authorities ordered to sell the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> only to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304" type="subject">refugees</term>, not to the local population.</p>

			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304" type="subject">refugees</term> continued to move on the road
				toward <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/776175/biala-podlaska.html">Biała Podlaska</placeName> and Brest. Local inhabitants,
				afraid of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombings</term>, had started to leave the
				town already on the <date when="1939-09-07">7th [of September]</date>.</p>

			<p>On <date when="1939-09-07">7th</date>, there was a terrible <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083"
					type="subject">bombing</term> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759412/siedlce.html">Siedlce</placeName> (the local
				starosta [chief administrator] ordered the inhabitants to gather at a square – and the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">Germans</term> descended with their airplanes and
				threw <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombs</term> on the crowd of civilians – a
				lot of victims). Therefore, on the <date when="1939-09-07">7th</date>, to avoid a similar massacre, the starosta of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/760680/radzyn-podlaski.html">Radzyń Podlaski</placeName> ordered the population of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/764862/miedzyrzec-podlaski.html">Międzyrzec</placeName> (apparently by phone) to leave the town and
				go to the surrounding forests. In the night from the <date when="1939-09-07">7th</date> to the <date when="1939-09-08">8th</date> the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">police</term> and the OPL [Obrona
				Przeciwlotnicza, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1105" type="subject">Anti-aircraft</term> defence] woke
				the inhabitants and so they went to the forests. The town was nearly deserted by 3.30 a.m. On the <date when="1939-09-08">8th</date>
				in the evening <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320010_02.jpg"/>, at about 7 p.m., the population returned to the town.</p>

			<p>On the <date when="1939-09-10">10th [of September]</date>, at 9 a.m., I left <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/764862/miedzyrzec-podlaski.html">Międzyrzec</placeName> in the company of six comrades (<persName
					ref="#ehri_et_alter_victor">Victor Alter</persName>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_goldstein_bernard">Bernard Goldstein</persName>
				<note type="gloss">Well known Bund activists in prewar Poland.</note> and four young <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>), intending to go to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> and to participate in the defence of the city.</p>

			<p>On the road the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">army</term> did not let us <note
					type="gloss">In this part of the testimony, there are no personal pronouns and no auxiliary verbs (probably in order to save
					time), so it is not clear if it is the 1st person (singular or plural), or an impersonal form.</note> to go to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName>. Therefore, we set out to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName> – on foot, sometimes by a horse and wagon – and in this way we
				reached the city.</p>

			<p>The peasants on the road were friendly. One of them even gave us a lift on his wagon to the next town for free.</p>

			<p>We entered <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName> on the <date when="1939-09-10">10th</date>,
				Monday in the morning, after the city had already been severely <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083"
					type="subject">bombed</term>. A lot of ruins.</p>

			<p>In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName> special Jewish workers’ groups were created (the
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Polish</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">militia</term> did not accepted any Jews) in order
				to clean up the ruins, help to extinguish fires and so on. They <note type="gloss">In this part of the testimony, there are no
					personal pronouns and no auxiliary verbs (probably in order to save time), so it is not clear if it is the 1st person (singular or
					plural), or an impersonal form.</note> worked hard.</p>

			<p>On the <date type="1939-09-14">14th</date> a single issue of the newspaper <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html"
					>Lubliner</placeName> shtime [The Voice of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName>], the
				organ of the central committee of the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-1172">Bund</orgName>, was
				published.</p>

			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_alter_victor">Victor Alter</persName> stayed in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html"
					>Lublin</placeName>. He was appointed the Jewish press-officer by the city council and a member of its propaganda department.</p>

			<p>On the <date when="1939-09-14">14th</date> I [set out] on foot toward <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/774558/chelm.html"
					>Chełm</placeName> with two comrades.</p>

			<p>Before we reached <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/774558/chelm.html">Chełm</placeName> (on the <date when="1939-09-15"
					>15th</date>), about 12 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">German</term> airplanes
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombed</term> the road full of civilian <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304" type="subject">refugees</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-623" type="subject">evacuated</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">policemen</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">military</term> troops. They started to shoot when
				the troops had already passed, and aimed at civilians.</p>

			<p>On the road to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/774558/chelm.html">Chełm</placeName> we entered <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3089217/piaski.html">Piaski</placeName> (on the <date when="1939-09-14">14th</date>). In the town,
				perhaps two Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">families</term> remained. The
				others had <pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-WL05320010_03.jpg"/> already run away. Among non-Jews also only few remained. In the evening
				airplanes arrived, flying very low, right over the roofs. They shot from machine guns (did not make any <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-132" type="subject">victims</term>) and set fire to a house outside of the
				town.</p>

			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/774558/chelm.html">Chełm</placeName> was crowded with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1097" type="subject">soldiers</term>. The town was constantly <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombed</term>. A lot of ruins. I myself saw a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">military</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term> being destroyed.</p>

			<p>In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/774558/chelm.html">Chełm</placeName> I went to the PKU [Powiatowa Komenda Uzupełnień,
				District Recruiting Command], as I wanted to join the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076"
					type="subject">army</term>. They told me to go to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/704617/kovel.html">Kovel</placeName>. So
				I went to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/704617/kovel.html">Kovel</placeName>.</p>
